{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_38","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"curl -L 'https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12599735/' | rg -i -C 2 'fundus|uterine fundus|fundus uteri|dome|superior'\"","aggregated_output":"</div>\n</div></section></section><section aria-label=\"Article content\"><section class=\"body main-article-body\"><section class=\"abstract\" id=\"abstract1\"><h2>Abstract</h2>\n<p>Previous female pelvic organ models have predominantly been solid models, which do not accurately reflect the true anatomical structure of the human body. To construct anatomically accurate cavity three-dimensional reconstruction models of female pelvic cavity organs based on in vivo human magnetic resonance imaging (MRI). Based on pelvic MRI from 120 patients, we measured organ wall thickness and anatomical variation to obtain population-averaged wall-thickness parameters (mean ± SD). Using these parameters, we constructed a single representative cavity model through segmentation, Non-Uniform Rational B-Spline surface reconstruction, and Boolean operations. This model represents an instance informed by population metrics rather than a voxel-by-voxel composite of all 120 scans. The present study focuses on visceral organ cavities (uterus, vagina, bladder, and rectum) and does not include pelvic body-wall musculature or bony structures. This was combined with Non-Uniform Rational B-Spline surface reconstruction in Ge-omagic Wrap and Boolean operations in SolidWorks to construct 4 major cavity entities: an irregular wall-thickened myometrial cavity with endometrial resection, a cervically enveloped upper semi-closed (lower open vaginal cavity, a semi-closed bladder cavity with an open urethral end, and an open-ended rectal cavity). A standardized wall thickness parameter table (accuracy 0.01 mm) was established through double measurements by 2 independent operators, with final values derived from the mean of measurements. Anatomically characteristic cavity models were generated, forming an assembly that reflects the adjacency relationships of multiple organs. Measurement results of organ wall thickness, bladder wall 1.52 ± 0.28 mm (intraclass correlation coefficient [ICC] = 0.781), vaginal wall 3.97 ± 0.56 mm (ICC = 0.876), rectal wall 1.38 ± 0.19 mm (ICC = 0.824). This study used MRI-derived, population-averaged wall thickness to construct representative cavity models of female pelvic organs. The inputs showed good reproducibility (ICC), but external validation, such as cadaveric comparison or independent imaging, is still needed. These models provide a basis for teaching, preliminary simulations, and future finite-element analyses.</p>\n<section id=\"kwd-group1\" class=\"kwd-group\"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> cavity model, female pelvic organs, surgical simulation, teaching model, three-dimensional (3D) reconstruction</p></section></section><section id=\"sec1\"><h2 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">1. Introduction</h2>\n<p>Medical three-dimensional (3D) reconstruction technology was initially applied in orthopedics and dentistry,<sup>[<a href=\"#R1\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R1\">1</a>]</sup> later expanding to complex organ reconstruction. Based on computed tomography and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI),<sup>[<a href=\"#R2\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R2\">2</a>]</sup> its applications have evolved from early auxiliary diagnosis<sup>[<a href=\"#R1\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R1\">1</a>]</sup> to surgical planning,<sup>[<a href=\"#R3\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R3\">3</a>]</sup> medical education,<sup>[<a href=\"#R4\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R4\">4</a>,<a href=\"#R5\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R5\">5</a>]</sup> and now to patient communication,<sup>[<a href=\"#R6\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R6\">6</a>]</sup> making significant contributions to the medical field. MRI 3D reconstruction technology is crucial for studying female pelvic organs. The MRI data in Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine format undergoes processing, including mask construction, threshold segmentation, and multilayer editing using the Mimics 21.0 (Materialise N.V., Leuven, Belgium) software system to generate a point cloud model with anatomical authenticity.<sup>[<a href=\"#R7\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R7\">7</a>]</sup> Although this model has characteristics such as a streamlined data structure and efficient computation, it is limited by a lack of surface realism and non-solidification defects, necessitating its export in stereolithography (STL) format to reverse engineering software for solid reconstruction.<sup>[<a href=\"#R8\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R8\">8</a>]</sup> In Geomagic Wrap 2021 (3D Systems, Rock Hill, SC), point cloud preprocessing transforms irregular free-form surfaces into NURBS (Non-Uniform Rational B-Spline) surface patches, significantly improving surface smoothness and geometric accuracy, ultimately generating a solid model with complete geometric topology information.<sup>[<a href=\"#R9\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"R9\">9</a>]</sup> SolidWorks 2023 (Dassault Systèmes, Waltham, MA) effectively supports the modeling of female pelvic organs with complex cavities and duct structures through functions such as nested reduction and assembly mating.</p>\n--\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/F1/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>Flowchart of the overall study design and modeling workflow. Schematic overview illustrating the sequential stages of the study, from patient data acquisition to the final assembled model. Key steps include magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), image segmentation and initial model generation, organ wall thickness measurement, cavity model construction for individual organs (uterus, vagina, bladder, and rectum), and the final assembly process. DICOM = Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine; NURBS = Non-Uniform Rational B-Splines; STL = stereolithography.</p></figcaption></figure><p>This model development study used pelvic MRI data from 120 patients collected at Nanfang Hospital between January 2022 and September 2023. Wall thicknesses and anatomical variations of the uterus, vagina, bladder, and rectum were measured to obtain population-averaged parameters (mean ± standard deviation [SD]). These averaged parameters were then applied to construct a single representative cavity model. The model focuses on visceral organ cavities and does not include pelvic body-wall musculature or bony structures.</p>\n<p>All patients were admitted for gynecological diseases meeting the MRI inclusion criteria, such as endometrial atypical hyperplasia, endometrial cancer, ovarian cyst, etc. Excluding cases where large pelvic masses cause deformation and displacement of pelvic organs. This study was approved by the Ethics Committee of Nanfang Hospital, Southern Medical University. The requirement for informed consent was waived by the ethics committee due to the retrospective nature of the study and the use of anonymized clinical data.</p>\n<p><em>Imaging acquisition</em>: utilization of the Philips Achieva TX 3.0T MRI Scanner (Philips Healthcare, Netherlands), coupled with an octochannel abdominal coil.</p>\n<p><em>Sequence parameters</em>: using standardized T2-weighted Turbo Spin Echo sequences, multiplanar images were acquired. Axial sections extended from lumbar vertebra L5 to 1 cm below the perineum; sagittal views encompassed both ischial spines, while coronal cuts ranged from the pubic symphysis to the coccyx. Specific technical details included repetition time/echo time settings of 3000 to 5000 ms/85 ms, a flip angle of 180°, field of view dimensions of 260 mm × 360 mm × 262 mm, a matrix of 512 × 512, a slice thickness of 3.0 mm, and an interslice gap of 0.5 mm. Each scan required approximately 7 to 8 minutes to complete.</p>\n<section id=\"sec3\"><h3 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">2.1. 3D reconstruction of the bladder (including the urethra), vagina, uterus, endometrium, and rectum based on MRI imaging layers</h3>\n<p>In Mimics 21.0, pelvic organ segmentation is accomplished through a systematic work-flow: select “File” → “New Project,” and ensure the inclusion of the T2-Weighted Turbo Spin Echo-Axial sequence/T2-weighted Turbo Spin Echo sequence scan images. Utilizing the interconnected axial, sagittal, and coronal view windows, the anatomical boundaries of the bladder, vagina, and rectum are delineated layer by layer, which ensures sufficient visualization of the myometrium and endometrial structures via sequential observation. To create masks for the bladder, vagina, and rectum, the initial contours of the organs are manually delineated in the axial view window, guided by the gray histogram distribution characteristics of the MRI images. By employing window leveling technology to enhance the density difference boundaries (i.e., imaging grayscale thresholds) between the bladder wall, vaginal wall, rectal wall, and surrounding tissues, a 3D point cloud model of the organ surface (a nonsolid shell structure composed of discrete points) is generated through the image segmentation process, which includes Mask Creation, Thresholding, Region Growing, Multiple Edit, and Mask Smoothing. This model is then exported in STL format, as illustrated in (Fig. <a href=\"#F2\" class=\"usa-link\">2</a>A–D), which depicts the MRI 3D reconstruction of the bladder, uterus, endometrium, vagina, and rectum.</p>\n<figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"F2\"><h4 class=\"obj_head\">Figure 2.</h4>\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><a class=\"tileshop\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12599735_medi-104-e45931-g002.jpg\"><img class=\"graphic zoom-in\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/af05/12599735/cdb27a16bcd4/medi-104-e45931-g002.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" height=\"400\" width=\"800\" alt=\"Figure 2.\"></a></p>\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/F2/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>Extraction of MRI data, identification, delineation, and 3D reconstruction of the bladder, uterus, endometrium, vagina, and rectum. (A) Coronal plane (Coronal); (B) axial plane (axial); (C) sagittal plane (sagittal); (D) 3D reconstruction of the bladder, uterus (pink), endometrium (yellow), vagina (purple), and rectum (brown). MRI = magnetic resonance imaging.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id=\"sec4\"><h3 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">2.2. Principle and anatomical locations for wall thickness measurement</h3>\n<p>The wall thicknesses of the bladder, vagina, and rectum were measured on the axial T2-weighted MRI sequences. To ensure anatomical relevance and consistency, measurements were performed at standardized locations for each organ (Fig. <a href=\"#F3\" class=\"usa-link\">3</a>):</p>\n<figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"F3\"><h4 class=\"obj_head\">Figure 3.</h4>\n--\n<li><p>These final mean values were used to establish a standardized wall thickness parameter table (accuracy: 0.01 mm), which provided the empirical basis for the subsequent cavity model reconstruction.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>The intraclass correlation coefficient (ICC) was subsequently used to assess the interobserver reliability of this measurement protocol (see Section 2.7).</p></section><section id=\"sec6\"><h3 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">2.4. Method for constructing a muscular uterine cavity entity to reduce irregular wall thickness of the endometrium</h3>\n<p>In Mimics 21.0, the process begins with the axial MRI sequences, where the window width and level are adjusted alongside histogram-guided contour tracing techniques to construct the uterine and endometrial masks layer by layer (including 1–2 continuous slices to ensure 3D continuity), strictly adhering to the anatomical termination points of the internal cervical os. Through threshold segmentation, region growing, and mask smoothing, non-interfering STL point clouds are generated. Subsequently, in Geomagic Wrap, point cloud preprocessing (including spike removal, noise reduction, and hole filling), triangular mesh optimization, and NURBS surface reconstruction (grid construction and topological repair) are performed, resulting in the export of STEP/Parasolid solid models of the uterus and endometrium. Following this, in Solid-Works 2023, spatial registration is conducted: the origins of the uterine–endometrial coordinate systems are aligned using the “multiple mating mode” to construct an anatomically precise nested assembly. Finally, a Boolean subtraction operation (uterine body minus the duplicated endometrial tool body) is utilized to generate a solid model of the irregularly thick-walled muscular cavity (Fig. <a href=\"#F4\" class=\"usa-link\">4</a>A), whose natural anatomical structural characteristics directly support biomechanical simulations.</p>\n<figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"F4\"><h4 class=\"obj_head\">Figure 4.</h4>\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><a class=\"tileshop\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12599735_medi-104-e45931-g004.jpg\"><img class=\"graphic zoom-in\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/af05/12599735/d0632b13748e/medi-104-e45931-g004.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" height=\"436\" width=\"800\" alt=\"Figure 4.\"></a></p>\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/F4/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>(A) Solid model of the muscular uterine cavity with nonuniform thickness (including endometrium); (B) solid model of the upper fully enclosed structure with uniform thickness and the lower open cavity of the vagina; (C) solid model of the bladder cavity with the urethral orifice open and the main body of the bladder semi-enclosed (including the urethra); (D) solid model of the rectal cavity open at both ends.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id=\"sec7\"><h3 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">2.5. Construction of hollow organ modeling methods for bladder, vagina, and rectum with uniform wall thickness</h3>\n<ol class=\"list\" style=\"list-style-type:decimal\">\n<li><p>The method for solid modeling of the vaginal cavity with a semi-closed upper segment and an open lower segment nested around the cervical morphology (Fig. <a href=\"#F4\" class=\"usa-link\">4</a>B).</p></li>\n<li><p>Import the vaginal point cloud in STL format into Geomagic Wrap. Generate a polygonal mesh through point cloud preprocessing, which includes denoising, hole filling, and smoothing. Subsequently, output the solid vaginal model in STEP or Parasolid format by performing contour editing and surface reconstruction. Next, align the coordinate system in the Polygon module and execute a planar cut to obtain a shell structure with a closed upper end and an open lower end. Following this, generate a uniformly thick vaginal cavity based on MRI-measured thickness through shell offset and reconstruct it as a NURBS surface after topology optimization. Finally, import the vaginal cavity and the pre-built uterus–endometrium assembly into SolidWorks, achieve spatial alignment via coordinate system registration, and apply Boolean subtraction to eliminate penetrating geometries. This process ultimately yields a joint model with a precise anatomical structure, featuring a semi-closed upper end (cervical embedding area), an open lower end, and topology corrections.</p></li>\n<li><p>The semi-closed bladder cavity with an open urethral orifice (including the urethra) entity.</p></li>\n\r100  158k  100  158k    0     0   579k      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--  582k\n<li><p>Import the STL format point cloud into Geomagic Wrap and generate a solid model of the bladder, including the urethra, through point cloud preprocessing techniques such as denoising, hole filling, and smoothing. Export the model in STEP/Parasolid format. Next, adjust the global coordinate system in the polygon module to ensure that the cutting plane is parallel to the end of the urethral orifice. Remove redundant geometry using planar section cutting to create a thickness-less shell with an open end at the urethral orifice and a semi-closed bladder body. Subsequently, perform a shelling operation based on the average bladder cavity thickness measured by MRI (with an accuracy of 0.01 mm) to generate a cavity model. Optimize the sharp geometry at the cutting edge of the urethral orifice through spike removal, mesh relaxation, noise filtering, and surface smoothing. Finally, complete the anatomically accurate cavity solid modeling (Fig. <a href=\"#F4\" class=\"usa-link\">4</a>C) using NURBS surface reconstruction, which includes contour topology optimization and surface patch repair, followed by grid verification. Export the final model in STEP/Parasolid format and save it.</p></li>\n--\n<li><p>Import the STL format point cloud into Geomagic Wrap and construct a solid rectal model through standardized preprocessing, which includes noise reduction, hole filling, and smoothing. Next, export the model in STEP or Parasolid format. Subsequently, adjust the global coordinate system in the polygon module to align the cutting plane parallel to the anatomical starting segment of the rectum. Remove redundant geometry using planar section cutting to generate an open-ended rectal shell without thickness at both ends. Then, perform a shelling operation based on the average thickness of the rectal cavity, as measured by MRI with a precision of 0.01 mm. Optimize the anatomical morphology of the sharp edges at the open ends through spike removal, mesh relaxation, noise filtering, and surface smoothing. Finally, complete the modeling of a 2-end open cavity solid that conforms to the physiological structure of the rectum (Fig. <a href=\"#F4\" class=\"usa-link\">4</a>D) using NURBS surface reconstruction technology, which includes contour topology optimization and surface patch repair, followed by grid verification. Export the final model in STEP or Parasolid format.</p></li>\n</ol></section><section id=\"sec8\"><h3 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">2.6. High-precision solid model of pelvic organs constructed based on reverse engineering in SolidWorks 2023 software</h3>\n<p>Perform multi-body assembly operations on the semi-closed bladder cavity entity, which includes an open urethral orifice (including the urethra), the muscular uterine cavity entity characterized by irregular wall thickness following endometrial reduction, the upper semi-closed and lower open vaginal cavity entity nested around the cervical morphology, and the rectal cavity entity that is open at both ends. Import the cavity models of each organ in STEP/X-T format into SolidWorks 2023 software and save the models of each female pelvic organ in SLDPRT part format. Open the assembly environment, import the SLDPRT part format of each female pelvic organ model, and establish initial spatial positioning by registering the global coordinate system origin. Apply distance constraints and angle constraints based on anatomical landmarks as necessary to achieve dynamic adaptation of the adjacent relationships among multiple organs. Finally, generate a pelvic system assembly that exhibits anatomical continuity and conforms to the real human anatomical structure and accurate organ adjacency relationships (Fig. <a href=\"#F5\" class=\"usa-link\">5</a>A–D). This assembly preserves NURBS surface parameters, material properties, and spatial constraint relationships through the STEP AP242 standard and is saved in either the assembly SLDASM format or the part format SLDPRT.</p>\n<figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"F5\"><h4 class=\"obj_head\">Figure 5.</h4>\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><a class=\"tileshop\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12599735_medi-104-e45931-g005.jpg\"><img class=\"graphic zoom-in\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/af05/12599735/50452707bc17/medi-104-e45931-g005.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" height=\"521\" width=\"800\" alt=\"Figure 5.\"></a></p>\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/F5/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>High-precision solid models of pelvic organs based on origin assembly: semi-enclosed bladder cavity with open urethral orifice (including urethra) in green; muscular uterine cavity with irregular wall thickness excluding endometrium in pink; semi-enclosed upper segment and open lower segment vaginal cavity surrounding the cervical morphology in purple; open-ended rectal cavity in brown. <em>Noted</em>: (A) right view; (B) left view (cross-section); (C) bottom view; (D) top view.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id=\"sec9\"><h3 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">2.7. Statistical analysis</h3>\n<p>Statistical analysis was performed using SPSS 26.0 (IBM Corporation, Armonk) and GraphPad Prism 9.5 (GraphPad Software, LLC, San Diego). The normality of continuous variables was assessed using the Shapiro–Wilk test, and normally distributed data are presented as mean ± SD.</p>\n<p>The ICC was used to quantify the interobserver reliability of the wall thickness measurements performed on the MRI images by the 2 independent operators. The ICC analysis was applied to the 4 repeated measurements (2 operators × 2 repetitions each) for the bladder, vaginal, and rectal walls. A high ICC value indicates that the measurements were consistent and reproducible between the operators, ensuring the reliability of the mean wall thickness values that were subsequently used to parameterize the 3D cavity models.</p>\n--\n<p>Cavity models of 4 female pelvic organs were constructed, incorporating the MRI-derived mean wall thickness measurements:</p>\n<ol class=\"list\" style=\"list-style-type:decimal\">\n<li><p>A myometrial cavity with irregular wall thickness following endometrial resection.</p></li>\n<li><p>A vaginal cavity with a mean wall thickness of 3.97 ± 0.56 mm (mean ± SD), featuring a semi-closed upper segment nested around the cervix and an open distal end (Fig. <a href=\"#F3\" class=\"usa-link\">3</a>B).</p></li>\n<li><p>A bladder cavity with a mean wall thickness of 1.52 ± 0.28 mm, featuring a semi-closed body and an open urethral orifice (including urethral structure, Fig. <a href=\"#F3\" class=\"usa-link\">3</a>C).</p></li>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_40","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"curl -L 'https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11304927/' | rg -i -C 2 'fundus|uterine fundus|fundus uteri|dome|superior'\"","aggregated_output":"</div>\n</div></section></section><section aria-label=\"Article content\"><section class=\"body main-article-body\"><section class=\"abstract\" id=\"Abs1\"><h2>Abstract</h2>\n<p id=\"Par1\">Pseudo-Meigs syndrome is a rare syndrome characterized by hydrothorax and ascites associated with pelvic masses, and patients occasionally present with elevated serum cancer antigen-125 (CA125) levels. Hydropic leiomyoma (HLM) is an uncommon subtype of uterine leiomyoma characterized by hydropic degeneration and secondary cystic changes. Rapidly enlarging HLMs accompanied by hydrothorax, ascites, and elevated CA125 levels may be misdiagnosed as malignant tumors. Here, we report a case of HLM in a 45-year-old Chinese woman who presented with ascites and hydrothorax. Preoperative abdominopelvic CT revealed a giant solid mass in the fundus uteri measuring 20 × 15 × 12 cm. Her serum CA125 level was elevated to 247.7 U/ml, while her hydrothorax CA125 level was 304.60 U/ml. The patient was initially diagnosed with uterine malignancy and underwent total abdominal hysterectomy and adhesiolysis. Pathological examination confirmed the presence of a uterine hydropic leiomyoma with cystic changes. After tumor removal, the ascites and hydrothorax subsided quickly, with no evidence of recurrence. The patient’s serum CA125 level decreased to 116.90 U/mL on Day 7 and 5.6 U/mL on Day 40 postsurgery. Follow-up data were obtained at 6 months, 1 year, and 2 years after surgery, and no recurrence of ascites or hydrothorax was observed. This case highlights the importance of accurate diagnosis and appropriate management of HLM to achieve successful outcomes.</p>\n<section id=\"kwd-group1\" lang=\"en\" class=\"kwd-group\"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Pseudo-Meigs syndrome, Hydropic leiomyoma, CA125</p></section></section><section id=\"Sec1\"><h2 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">Introduction</h2>\n<p id=\"Par2\">Pseudo-Meigs syndrome is a rare condition characterized by ascites and hydrothorax, along with masses in the abdomen and pelvis, similar to Meigs syndrome, which is usually associated with ovarian fibromas or fibroid tumors. Surgical removal of the tumor leads to the rapid resolution of symptoms and a good outcome [<a href=\"#CR1\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR1\">1</a>]. Tumors linked to pseudo-Meigs syndrome include uterine cancer [<a href=\"#CR2\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR2\">2</a>], metastatic cancer [<a href=\"#CR3\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR3\">3</a>], ovarian struma ovarii [<a href=\"#CR4\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR4\">4</a>], and uterine leiomyoma [<a href=\"#CR5\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR5\">5</a>]. Uterine leiomyoma is the most common benign tumor of the female reproductive system, and the diagnostic methods for these tumors include ultrasound examination, transvaginal ultrasound examination, computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI). The clinical behavior and imaging features of leiomyomas can vary, especially in those with degenerative changes, which make it difficult to distinguish them from malignant tumors in the uterus or ovaries. Pseudo-Meigs syndrome caused by uterine leiomyoma in patients with elevated CA125 levels is extremely rare, with only a few cases reported in the literature, and this syndrome be mistaken for ovarian cancer or uterine sarcoma. Accurate diagnosis is crucial for appropriate treatment. We present the case of a 45-year-old Chinese woman with a rapidly growing pelvic mass, ascites, hydrothorax, and elevated CA125 levels who was initially misdiagnosed with a malignancy. Pathological examination revealed a large uterine leiomyoma with hydropic degeneration and cystic changes. This case highlights the importance of recognizing pseudo-Meigs syndrome in patients with elevated CA125 levels caused by uterine leiomyoma and emphasizes the need for accurate diagnosis, appropriate treatment, and an improved understanding of patient prognosis.</p></section><section id=\"Sec2\"><h2 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">Case report</h2>\n<p id=\"Par3\">A 45-year-old Chinese woman presented with complaints of abdominal distension and intermittent abdominal pain. She was admitted to the gynecology department of our hospital. Her medical and family history was unremarkable. Menarche occurred at the age of 13 years, and her menstrual cycles were regular. An abdominopelvic MRI revealed a solid mass measuring 7.3 × 6.1 × 6.9 cm in the fundus uteri. The patient was discharged without intervention. Eight months later, the patient returned to the gynecology department with complaints of abdominal pain, discomfort in the lower-abdominal region, and vaginal bleeding.</p>\n<p id=\"Par4\">Physical examination revealed the presence of a large, solid mass on the right side of the lower abdomen, with no other abnormalities detected. Palpation revealed tenderness in the area of the mass, which filled the pelvic cavity. An abdominopelvic CT scan revealed a cystic solid mass located in the posterior wall of the uterus. The mass measured 14.7 × 11.3 × 12.7 cm in size and was accompanied by a significant amount of ascites (Figs. <a href=\"#Fig1\" class=\"usa-link\">1</a> and <a href=\"#Fig2\" class=\"usa-link\">2</a>). The solid component demonstrated clear and uniform enhancement on enhanced scanning, in contrast to the low-density area. A chest CT scan revealed the presence of a right hydrothorax. The initial diagnosis favored an ovarian tumor or leiomyoma with degeneration. Prior to surgery, 6 L of hydrothorax fluid and 6 L of ascites fluid were collected for laboratory examination and cytology. The results revealed elevated levels of CA125 in both the serum and hydrothorax, with values of 304.60 U/mL and 247.7 U/mL, respectively (normal values &lt; 35 U/mL). The levels of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), luteinizing hormone (LH), estradiol, progesterone, prolactin, testosterone II, total protein, albumin, lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), and carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) were within the normal ranges in all the samples. Cytology was negative for malignant cells or <em>Mycobacterium tuberculosis</em>.</p>\n<figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"Fig1\"><h3 class=\"obj_head\">Fig. 1.</h3>\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><img class=\"graphic\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/2f35f2cd35cf/12905_2024_3285_Fig1_HTML.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" id=\"d33e244\" height=\"646\" width=\"646\" alt=\"Fig. 1\"></p>\n--\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><img class=\"graphic\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/d08e92c5efbe/12905_2024_3285_Fig2_HTML.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" id=\"d33e254\" height=\"646\" width=\"646\" alt=\"Fig. 2\"></p>\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/Fig2/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>Contrast-enhanced CT (sagittal view) revealed a giant mass measuring 14 × 12 × 10 cm in size in the pelvis, with a noted cyst in the center (blue arrow)</p></figcaption></figure><p id=\"Par7\">According to imaging tests and laboratory analyses, the patient was diagnosed with either ovarian cancer or leiomyosarcoma before surgery. Total abdominal hysterectomy was performed, along with excision of the mass and adhesiolysis. Intraoperative observations revealed a distinct subserosal solid tumor arising from the uterine fundus and extending into the pelvic cavity, accompanied by a moderate quantity of light-red ascites.</p>\n<p id=\"Par8\">The tumor measured 20 × 15 × 12 cm on gross examination. The cut surface of the tumor exhibited a pale and fleshy appearance, with evidence of hydropic and cystic degeneration. No evidence of hemorrhage or necrosis was observed (Fig. <a href=\"#Fig3\" class=\"usa-link\">3</a>). Microscopic examination revealed that the tumor demonstrated the typical characteristics of a leiomyoma, with no evidence of myometrial or vascular invasion. The tumor cells demonstrated mild cytologic atypia, with no mitoses or necrosis present, and were surrounded by edema or a watery matrix (Figs. <a href=\"#Fig4\" class=\"usa-link\">4</a> and <a href=\"#Fig5\" class=\"usa-link\">5</a>). Immunohistochemical staining revealed diffuse positivity for h-Caldesmon (Fig. <a href=\"#Fig6\" class=\"usa-link\">6</a>) and desmin but negativity for HMB45, Melan-A, CD10, P16, and P53. The Ki67 index was less than 1%. A pathological diagnosis of hydropic leiomyoma was established on the basis of these findings.</p>\n<figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"Fig3\"><h3 class=\"obj_head\">Fig. 3.</h3>\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><img class=\"graphic\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/d663608f0c49/12905_2024_3285_Fig3_HTML.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" id=\"d33e280\" height=\"732\" width=\"646\" alt=\"Fig. 3\"></p>\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/Fig3/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>Gross examination revealed a solid grayish-white tumor located at the uterine fundus that protruded into the pelvic cavity (blue arrow). The cut surface was grayish-white and fleshy with water degeneration and cystic changes (red arrow)</p></figcaption></figure><figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"Fig4\"><h3 class=\"obj_head\">Fig. 4.</h3>\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><img class=\"graphic\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6c29/11304927/3bebb6aff491/12905_2024_3285_Fig4_HTML.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" id=\"d33e290\" height=\"540\" width=\"646\" alt=\"Fig. 4\"></p>\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/Fig4/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n--\n<p id=\"Par15\">In 1937, ovarian fibroma accompanied by ascites and hydrothorax was first described by Meigs and Cass. In 1954, Meigs reviewed the cases of 84 patients who presented with rapid resolution of ascites and/or hydrothorax following the removal of ovarian fibromas or fibroma-like tumors. These patients were subsequently diagnosed with Meigs syndrome [<a href=\"#CR6\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR6\">6</a>]. Pseudo-Meigs syndrome, similar to Meigs syndrome, is frequently associated with ovarian cancer, metastatic tumors, mature teratoma, struma ovarii, borderline tumors, and uterine leiomyoma [<a href=\"#CR7\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR7\">7</a>, <a href=\"#CR8\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR8\">8</a>]. The clinical features of pseudo-Meigs syndrome include the presence of a large pelvic mass, recurrent ascites and hydrothorax. The presence of elevated CA125 levels in patient with pseudo-Meigs syndrome can result in the misdiagnosis of malignancy with pelvic and pleural metastases, resulting in unnecessary treatment. Patients with pseudo-Meigs syndrome who have elevated CA125 levels caused by uterine leiomyoma are exceedingly rare and are likely to be misdiagnosed [<a href=\"#CR1\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR1\">1</a>]. This report describes a case of pseudo-Meigs syndrome caused by a rapidly enlarging uterine hydropic leiomyoma in a patient with elevated CA125 levels, and a review of the relevant literature is provided.</p>\n<p id=\"Par16\">The etiology of ascites and hydrothorax remains unclear, with several hypotheses proposed for the development of ascites: (1) Mechanical irritation of the peritoneum by a large tumor may lead to pelvic inflammation and fluid accumulation [<a href=\"#CR6\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR6\">6</a>, <a href=\"#CR9\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR9\">9</a>, <a href=\"#CR10\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR10\">10</a>]; (2) fluid secretion due to lymphatic obstruction, increased permeability of the neovasculature from tumor pedicle torsion, and low serum protein levels may occur [<a href=\"#CR11\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR11\">11</a>–<a href=\"#CR13\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR13\">13</a>]; and (3) cytokines and inflammatory mediators may promote the production of ascites, with studies demonstrating that elevated serum vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) is associated with ascites and hydrothorax [<a href=\"#CR14\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR14\">14</a>]. Furthermore, cytokines such as VEGF, fibroblast growth factor (FGF), and interleukin (IL)-6 have been demonstrated to stimulate mesothelial cells and promote ascites and hydrothorax in patients with Meigs’ syndrome or pseudo-Meigs syndrome, with levels returning to normal following tumor removal [<a href=\"#CR15\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR15\">15</a>]. Further research has revealed the pivotal role of VEGF, FGF, IL-1β, IL-6, and IL-8 in the development of ascites and hydrothorax [<a href=\"#CR16\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR16\">16</a>]. In patients with pseudo-Meigs syndrome, right-sided hydrothorax is more common due to developmental defects in the right hemidiaphragm, typically occurring approximately 3 h after ascites formation and potentially originating from pelvic effusions [<a href=\"#CR11\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR11\">11</a>].</p>\n<p id=\"Par17\">The occurrence of Meigs syndrome or pseudo-Meigs syndrome in conjunction with elevated CA125 levels is relatively uncommon, and the underlying mechanism remains unclear [<a href=\"#CR8\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR8\">8</a>, <a href=\"#CR17\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR17\">17</a>]. CA125, also known as MUC16, is a glycoprotein that was first identified in 1981 [<a href=\"#CR18\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR18\">18</a>]. CA125 is not considered a reliable marker for the diagnosis of malignancy because of its low sensitivity and specificity. Elevated CA125 levels can be observed in individuals with various benign and malignant conditions, such as pregnancy, pelvic inflammatory disease, endometriosis, tuberculosis, cirrhosis, and autoimmune diseases [<a href=\"#CR18\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR18\">18</a>, <a href=\"#CR19\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR19\">19</a>]. The CA125 present in ascites may be produced by activated mesothelial cells, whose expression is potentially upregulated by proinflammatory cytokines [<a href=\"#CR20\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR20\">20</a>].</p>\n\r100  176k  100  176k    0     0   757k      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--  759k\n<p id=\"Par18\">Pseudo-Meigs syndrome, caused by leiomyomas in patients with elevated CA125, is a rarer condition. A total of 24 cases have been documented in the English literature (Table <a href=\"#Tab1\" class=\"usa-link\">1</a>). Uterine leiomyomas are the most common benign tumors of the female reproductive system, with an incidence rate of approximately 70% [<a href=\"#CR21\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR21\">21</a>]. Approximately 50% of uterine leiomyomas undergo degenerative changes, including myxoid degeneration, hyalinosis, calcification, steatosis, red degeneration, watery degeneration, and cystic degeneration. These changes can be precipitated by pregnancy or hormonal therapy. Although degeneration of uterine leiomyomas can lead to rapid tumor enlargement, infiltration or metastasis is not observed [<a href=\"#CR22\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR22\">22</a>]. Edema leiomyoma or hydropic leiomyoma (HLM) is a rare subtype characterized by diffuse watery degeneration and secondary cystic changes [<a href=\"#CR23\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR23\">23</a>]. Such lesions may undergo rapid enlargement and may be misdiagnosed as leiomyosarcomas or ovarian malignancies. HLMs display characteristics distinct from those of typical leiomyomas, including differences in tumor size, edema area, extracellular matrix composition, vascular proliferation, and molecular genetic changes. Studies have demonstrated that t(4;8)(p16;q22) is a unique abnormality found in individuals with HLMs [<a href=\"#CR24\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR24\">24</a>]. Additionally, overexpression of the HMGA2 gene, <em>HMGA2</em> gene rearrangement, and increased pAKT activity have been identified in HLM patients, which strongly suggests a distinct association with HMGA2 overexpression [<a href=\"#CR25\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"CR25\">25</a>].</p>\n<section class=\"tw xbox font-sm\" id=\"Tab1\"><h3 class=\"obj_head\">Table 1.</h3>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_39","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"curl -L 'https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12358623/' | rg -i -C 2 'fundus|uterine fundus|fundus uteri|dome|superior'\"","aggregated_output":"<p id=\"p0025\">The term traditionally applied to clinically describe the presence of pelvic varicose veins associated with chronic pain is pelvic congestion syndrome. However, this terminology does not adequately capture the full spectrum of clinical presentations associated with this pathology. As a result, it has been extensively debated and has largely been replaced by the term pelvic venous disorders (PeVDs). This updated terminology integrates much more broader concepts and adopts a multidisciplinary perspective on venous disorders in this anatomical region, along with a standardization through the Symptoms-Varices-Pathophysiology classification of PeVDs.<a href=\"#bib5\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib5\"><sup>5</sup></a></p>\n<p id=\"p0030\">Regarding imaging diagnostic modalities for PeVD, several options are available, including Doppler ultrasound examination, computed tomography (CT) scan, magnetic resonance (MR) imaging, and phlebography. Among these, phlebography is recognized as the gold standard for diagnosing PeVDs.<a href=\"#bib4\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib4\"><sup>4</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib6\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib6\"><sup>6</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib7\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib7\"><sup>7</sup></a></p>\n<p id=\"p0035\">Transvaginal ultrasound (TVUS) examination has undergone significant advances in accuracy and diagnostic precision. Over the past decade, this technique has expanded its applicability in the examination of various pelvic organs and compartments, with a particular focus on improving the detection of deep endometriosis.<a href=\"#bib8\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib8\"><sup>8</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib9\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib9\"><sup>9</sup></a> These advances have not only allowed a thorough examination of gynecologic pathologies, but have also facilitated the analysis of additional structures, including the pelvic veins.</p>\n<p id=\"p0040\">TVUS examination offers key advantages in the evaluation of PeVDs, including real-time reflux assessment, high-resolution imaging of pelvic venous plexuses, and dynamic flow analysis without the need for radiation or contrast. Cross-sectional imaging techniques such as CT scan and MR imaging are typically performed with the patient in a flat supine position, which can limit the assessment of reflux and overestimate venous compressions due to the absence of gravitational effects. Although phlebography with intravascular ultrasound examination remains a reference standard in complex or inconclusive cases, it is invasive and not routinely used in initial evaluation. Nevertheless, CT, MR, and phlebography remain valuable tools when ultrasound examination is inconclusive, technically limited, or when complex anatomical variations are suspected.<a href=\"#bib10\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib10\">10</a>, <a href=\"#bib11\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib11\">11</a>, <a href=\"#bib12\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib12\">12</a>, <a href=\"#bib13\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib13\">13</a>, <a href=\"#bib14\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib14\">14</a></p>\n<section id=\"sec1\"><h2 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">Objective</h2>\n--\n</li>\n<li id=\"o0025\">\n<span class=\"label\">4.</span><p class=\"display-inline\" id=\"p0090\">Ovaries and gonadal veins: Locate the ovaries to assist in identifying gonadal veins, which course laterally and superiorly. Note the variability in ovarian position owing to uterine ligament asymmetry (<a href=\"#fig2\" class=\"usa-link\">Fig 2</a>, <em>A</em>-<em>C</em>).</p>\n</li>\n<li id=\"o0030\">\n--\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/fig4/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>Right external iliac vein: B-mode, color Doppler, and spectral Doppler <strong>(A-C)</strong>. Anatomical landmarks of the external iliac vein. External iliac artery B-mode, Color Doppler <strong>(D</strong> and <strong>E)</strong>, and psoas muscle <strong>(F)</strong>.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id=\"sec4.2\"><h3 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">Internal iliac vein</h3>\n<p id=\"p0125\">The internal iliac vein follows a vertical and oblique path, exhibiting a shorter length and smaller caliber than the external iliac vein. For accurate identification, it is essential to position the transducer towards the lateral pelvic wall, with the end facing downward toward the gluteal region. The main anatomical landmarks are the ovary, when located in its usual topography, and the internal iliac artery. The confluence of the external iliac vein can be identified, along with its anterior and posterior trunks (the anterior trunk drains the superior gluteal, ileolumbar, and lateral sacral regions; the other branches drain the posterior one) and its tributaries.<a href=\"#bib15\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib15\"><sup>15</sup></a> The ipsilateral ureter is an excellent structure for anatomical repair. It can be visualized in front of the internal iliac vessels and should be perceived as an anechoic tubular structure with no flow on color Doppler, exhibiting peristalsis (it fills and empties during the examination) (<a href=\"#fig5\" class=\"usa-link\">Fig 5</a>, <em>A</em>-<em>D</em>; <a href=\"#appsec1\" class=\"usa-link\">Supplementary Video 1</a>, online only).</p>\n<figure class=\"fig xbox font-sm\" id=\"fig5\"><h4 class=\"obj_head\">Fig 5.</h4>\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><a class=\"tileshop\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12358623_gr5.jpg\"><img class=\"graphic zoom-in\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6718/12358623/335efba2400e/gr5.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" height=\"153\" width=\"711\" alt=\"Fig 5\"></a></p>\n--\n<p class=\"img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center\"><a class=\"tileshop\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12358623_gr9.jpg\"><img class=\"graphic zoom-in\" src=\"https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/6718/12358623/18c8ff75ac63/gr9.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" height=\"795\" width=\"682\" alt=\"Fig 9\"></a></p>\n<div class=\"p text-right font-secondary\"><a href=\"figure/fig9/\" class=\"usa-link\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Open in a new tab</a></div>\n<figcaption><p>Detailed schematic representation of the pelvic escape points: clitoris point (<em>CP</em>), intermediate perineal point (<em>IPP</em>), posterior perineal point (<em>PP</em>), inguinal point (<em>IP</em>), obturator point (<em>OP</em>), inferior gluteal point (<em>IGP</em>), and superior gluteal point (<em>SGP</em>).</p></figcaption></figure></section></section><section id=\"sec5\"><h2 class=\"pmc_sec_title\">Discussion</h2>\n<p id=\"p0235\">Ultrasound examination is widely recognized as the first-line imaging modality for investigating PeVDs, using approaches such as transabdominal (TA), transvaginal (TVUS), transperineal, and venous mapping of the lower limbs.<a href=\"#bib1\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib1\"><sup>1</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib4\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib4\"><sup>4</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib11\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib11\"><sup>11</sup></a></p>\n<p id=\"p0240\">A TA approach is crucial for studying the iliocaval axis, focusing on issues such as venous compressions, post-thrombotic changes, and the search for tumor masses that may compress the vessels. It is also used, although less frequently, to detect congenital or acquired vascular abnormalities. However, for a more targeted examination of the pelvic veins, a transvaginal approach is preferred. This method provides superior visualization of the pelvic venous plexuses and internal iliac vein tributaries compared with a TA approach.<a href=\"#bib4\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib4\"><sup>4</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib19\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib19\"><sup>19</sup></a></p>\n\r100  158k  100  158k    0     0   601k      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--  603k\n<p id=\"p0245\">Therefore, we propose performing TVUS examination to study PVDs, focusing on the periuterine, perivaginal venous plexuses and gonadal and iliac veins. This imaging modality has high sensitivity and specificity for the diagnosis of pelvic varicose veins and the detection of reflux and post-thrombotic changes in the gonadal and iliac plexuses.<a href=\"#bib10\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib10\"><sup>10</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib18\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib18\"><sup>18</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib20\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib20\"><sup>20</sup></a></p>\n<p id=\"p0250\">The transvaginal transducer is characterized by its shorter wavelength and higher frequency compared with the convex (abdominal) transducer. Its proximity to the pelvic structures ensures greater resolution of images of organs and venous plexuses. This technique is also less affected by factors such as gases or body habitus. There is also an increase in the sensitivity of images obtained with color Doppler imaging, which allows better visualization of blood vessels, including veins that normally exhibit low velocity flow.<a href=\"#bib21\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib21\"><sup>21</sup></a></p>\n<p id=\"p0255\">Although it may be uncomfortable for some patients, it is superior to the TA, MR venography (MRV), or CT venography (CTV) for evaluating changes in flow direction during the Valsalva maneuver, using color and spectral Doppler examinations compared with the TA route, because with the latter modality, during the maneuver of effort, in most cases, the vein to be studied moves from its initial position and leaves the operator's field of vision, losing the ability to analyze and predict the presence of reflux.<a href=\"#bib4\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib4\"><sup>4</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib11\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib11\"><sup>11</sup></a></p>\n<p id=\"p0260\">A previous study conducted by our group demonstrated a sensitivity of 96% and a specificity of 100% in the detection of pelvic varicose veins using TVUS examination compared with phlebography.<a href=\"#bib10\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib10\"><sup>10</sup></a> Although the TA approach is useful for evaluating gonadal veins in the proximal segment, it does not provide an adequate analysis of venous reflux in the pelvic region. Additionally, it presents limitations in the visualization of the internal iliac veins and their tributaries, both at rest and during the Valsalva maneuver.<a href=\"#bib1\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib1\"><sup>1</sup></a> Furthermore, based on our experience, when a dilated gonadal vein with reflux is identified during the Valsalva maneuver using TVUS examination with Doppler, it is unusual not to find a corresponding abnormality detected via the abdominal route.<a href=\"#bib19\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib19\"><sup>19</sup></a></p>\n<p id=\"p0265\">In a comparative study of TA ultrasound and TVUS examination, 72 internal iliac veins were assessed. The results revealed that all 72 veins (100%) were successfully visualized using TVUS examination, whereas only 15 (21%) were identified by TA ultrasound examination. Of the 72 veins examined, 12 (17%) exhibited valve incompetence by TVUS examination, compared with only 2 (3%) identified by TA, both of which were detected by TVUS examination. The limitations of TA imaging are generally attributed to the presence of intestinal gas. The results indicate that TVUS examination has a higher success rate in detecting internal iliac vein reflux, suggesting that the TVUS method may be more sensitive and accurate than the TA approach.<a href=\"#bib19\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib19\"><sup>19</sup></a><sup>,</sup><a href=\"#bib20\" class=\"usa-link\" aria-describedby=\"bib20\"><sup>20</sup></a></p>\n--\n<span class=\"label\">7.</span><cite>Malgor R.D., Adrahtas D., Spentzouris G., Gasparis A.P., Tassiopoulos A.K., Labropoulos N. The role of duplex ultrasound in the workup of pelvic congestion syndrome. J Vasc Surg Venous Lymphatic Disord. 2014;2:34–38. doi: 10.1016/j.jvsv.2013.06.004.</cite> [<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jvsv.2013.06.004\" class=\"usa-link usa-link--external\" data-ga-action=\"click_feat_suppl\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">DOI</a>] [<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26992966/\" class=\"usa-link\">PubMed</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?journal=J%20Vasc%20Surg%20Venous%20Lymphatic%20Disord&amp;title=The%20role%20of%20duplex%20ultrasound%20in%20the%20workup%20of%20pelvic%20congestion%20syndrome&amp;author=R.D.%20Malgor&amp;author=D.%20Adrahtas&amp;author=G.%20Spentzouris&amp;author=A.P.%20Gasparis&amp;author=A.K.%20Tassiopoulos&amp;volume=2&amp;publication_year=2014&amp;pages=34-38&amp;pmid=26992966&amp;doi=10.1016/j.jvsv.2013.06.004&amp;\" class=\"usa-link usa-link--external\" data-ga-action=\"click_feat_suppl\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Google Scholar</a>]</li>\n<li id=\"bib8\">\n<span class=\"label\">8.</span><cite>Mais V., Guerriero S., Ajossa S., Angiolucci M., Paoletti A.M., Melis G.B. The efficiency of transvaginal ultrasonography in the diagnosis of endometrioma. Fertil Steril. 1993;60:776–780. doi: 10.1016/s0015-0282(16)56275-x.</cite> [<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/s0015-0282(16)56275-x\" class=\"usa-link usa-link--external\" data-ga-action=\"click_feat_suppl\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">DOI</a>] [<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8224260/\" class=\"usa-link\">PubMed</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?journal=Fertil%20Steril&amp;title=The%20efficiency%20of%20transvaginal%20ultrasonography%20in%20the%20diagnosis%20of%20endometrioma&amp;author=V.%20Mais&amp;author=S.%20Guerriero&amp;author=S.%20Ajossa&amp;author=M.%20Angiolucci&amp;author=A.M.%20Paoletti&amp;volume=60&amp;publication_year=1993&amp;pages=776-780&amp;pmid=8224260&amp;doi=10.1016/s0015-0282(16)56275-x&amp;\" class=\"usa-link usa-link--external\" data-ga-action=\"click_feat_suppl\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Google Scholar</a>]</li>\n<li id=\"bib9\">\n<span class=\"label\">9.</span><cite>Szabó G., Madár I., Hudelist G., et al.  Visualization of sacral nerve roots and sacral plexus on gynecological transvaginal ultrasound: feasibility study. Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol. 2023;62:290–299. doi: 10.1002/uog.26204.</cite> [<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1002/uog.26204\" class=\"usa-link usa-link--external\" data-ga-action=\"click_feat_suppl\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">DOI</a>] [<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36938682/\" class=\"usa-link\">PubMed</a>] [<a href=\"https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?journal=Ultrasound%20Obstet%20Gynecol&amp;title=Visualization%20of%20sacral%20nerve%20roots%20and%20sacral%20plexus%20on%20gynecological%20transvaginal%20ultrasound:%20feasibility%20study&amp;author=G.%20Szab%C3%B3&amp;author=I.%20Mad%C3%A1r&amp;author=G.%20Hudelist&amp;volume=62&amp;publication_year=2023&amp;pages=290-299&amp;pmid=36938682&amp;doi=10.1002/uog.26204&amp;\" class=\"usa-link usa-link--external\" data-ga-action=\"click_feat_suppl\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Google Scholar</a>]</li>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
